<div id="review_2251174632" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2251174632" />
    <a title="Cheri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3183576-cheri"><img alt="Cheri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1295716318p2/3183576.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2251174632?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cheri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cheri" href="/user/show/3183576-cheri">Cheri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8150764-baking-cakes-in-kigali">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3183576-cheri?shelf=food-nutrition">food-nutrition</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3183576-cheri?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3183576-cheri?shelf=africa">africa</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2251174632" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15149093397916445314">Generally I&apos;m not interested in feel-good books with homespun wisdom, but I gave this one a pass because it was set in Rwanda and helped concretize that country&apos;s troubled past for me. The characters&apos; stories read like a list of Africa&apos;s woes - genocide, broken families, trauma, hunger, AIDS, malaria, rape, female mutilation - and I would not have gotten through them all without the author&apos;s light touch and hopeful presentation. In the end it was an oddly uplifting book.</span>
  <span id="freeText15149093397916445314" style="display:none">Generally I'm not interested in feel-good books with homespun wisdom, but I gave this one a pass because it was set in Rwanda and helped concretize that country's troubled past for me. The characters' stories read like a list of Africa's woes - genocide, broken families, trauma, hunger, AIDS, malaria, rape, female mutilation - and I would not have gotten through them all without the author's light touch and hopeful presentation. In the end it was an oddly uplifting book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15149093397916445314" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


